y for its unsettling unpredictability, motion became the most certain way of comprehending social interactions, language, time, and the buildings that filtered human experience. At the heart of this narrative is the malleable sensory viewer, tacitly assumed in early modern architectural theory and history yet whose inescapable responsiveness to surrounding stimuli guaranteed a dependable world from the seventeenth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aART / History / General.2bisacsh  aEnglish architectural theorists.  aHeinrich Wolfflin.  achangeable garden.  adomestic built environment.  ageography.  ahuman experience.  aideal harmony.  amobile wall surface.  amobility.  amodern architectural theory.  apause.  aphilosophy.  apoetry.  apolitical theory.  aseventeenth-century England.  asocial divisions.  asocial interactions.  astaccato rhythms.  avistas.1 aSkelton, Kimberley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packagez978311128311140uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978071909827740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780719098277423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780719098277/original  a978-3-11-128311-1  Manchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packageb2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles